Plamodel-Style Programming Philosophy —
The Original Document of the Outer OS, Grammar Specification, and Black-Box Architecture (S)**

This philosophy, along with the Outer OS, grammar specification, and black‑box architecture,
was proposed, defined, and systematized by S (Shou).
This document serves as the official original source.

1. Background of This Philosophy
Modern programming assumes that “writing code” is the default.
However, in reality:

Beginners struggle with syntax

Experienced developers rewrite the same logic repeatedly

The market is filled with rigid templates

AI now generates massive amounts of code

Language barriers still remain

This situation has reached a structural limit.

Therefore, I conceived a philosophy that shifts programming
from “writing code” to “assembling components.”

2. What Is the Plamodel-Style Approach? (Definition)
The Plamodel-style approach is a philosophy where:

Programs are built as “components (logic units)”
and executed through “configuration” and “combination.”

Writing code is no longer the goal—
it becomes merely a tool for assembling components.

3. Problems This Philosophy Solves
■ Beginner Barriers
Syntax errors and environment setup stop progress

Nothing moves, so learning stalls

■ Inefficiency for Experienced Developers
Rewriting the same logic

Switching mental models between languages

■ Market Limitations
Templates are “finished products” with low extensibility

Logic authorship is not protected

■ Contradiction in the AI Era
AI writes code

Humans still learn under the assumption they must write it

The Plamodel-style approach solves these issues structurally.

4. Core Structure of the Philosophy
4‑1. Componentization (Minimal Logic Units)
Programs are extracted as “components.”
Each component is single‑purpose, reusable, and stable.

4‑2. Configuration (Changing Behavior Without Code)
Components change behavior through configuration files.
Beginners only modify settings.

4‑3. Combination (Building Features Like a Model Kit)
Complex features emerge by combining components—
just like assembling a plastic model.

4‑4. Rights Structure (Protecting Authors)
Logic authors retain copyright

Users receive only “usage rights”

Viewing rights are separate

Modification requires permission

4‑5. Market Structure (Components Become Assets)
More components → more value.
Network effects similar to an app store.

4‑6. Language Independence
Works in PHP, JavaScript, Python, and more.
The philosophy transcends technology.

4‑7. Alignment With the AI Era
AI writes code.
Humans focus on understanding, judging, and assembling.

5. Why Beginners Grow (Learning Model)
