9. Formal Definition of the Outer OS
I defined the Outer OS (Outer Structure OS),
which fixes the program’s grammar externally
while allowing internal logic to be replaced freely.

The Outer OS consists of three layers:

● parts / flow (Outer Grammar)
Application grammar is fixed externally.
No logic is written here.

● model (Receiver Layer)
Receives the outer grammar and passes it to the core.

● core (Logic Layer)
Executes the actual processing.
Completely separated from the outer grammar.

This three‑layer structure enables
complete separation of grammar and logic.

10. Black‑Box Architecture (Definition)
The central concept of the Outer OS is the Black Box.

A black box means:

Internal logic (core) is invisible

public and server are fully separated

Outer layer = grammar only

Inner layer = logic only

External modification of internal logic is impossible

The black box ensures security, rights protection, and market viability.

11. Original Grammar Specification (10 Actions)
I defined 10 fundamental actions  
that function as the outer grammar:

get_posts

get_item

filter

sort

paginate

render

save_db

delete_db

send_mail

auth

These form the minimal grammar  
usable across all applications
and serve as the foundation of the Outer OS.

12. Definition of the Market OS
Built on top of the Outer OS is the Market OS.

The Market OS includes:

Component categories (basic / extended / advanced)

Viewing rights

Author rights protection

Component sales

Network effects

Together, these form a new economic structure.

